R3.1: There is a already a constructor that takes no parameters that defaults the initial balance at $0;

R3.2: BankAccount b = new BankAccount(5000) creates a new reference 'b' pointing towards the object 
	  BankAccount with $5000 in it.
	  BankAccount b only creates a reference called 'b' that does not store anything.
 
R3.3: new BankAccount(5000) creates a new object BankAccount. BankAccount b = new BankAccount(5000) creates
	  a new object BankAccount with $5000 and a reference 'b' pointing to that object.
	  
R3.7: The this keyword is a reference to the current object. Its used to distinguish variables of the same name.
	  
R3.11: A local variable exists solely within the code block it is created/used in. 
	   A parameter variable is passed in to the method from the caller
	   
R3.12: A local variable exists solely within the code block it is created in. An instance field exists throughout
	   the entire class.
